Chief economist at Stanlib Kevin Lings analyses the repo rate cut. Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - The Reserve Bank announced a decision to cut rates by 25 basis points on Thursday. The decision is in line with analyst predictions, saying the ground is fertile for a cut. The reduction will take the prime lending rate at banks down to 10 percent. READ: Significant petrol price drop for July Lesetja Kganyago, SARB governor, said based on recent short term indicators for the mining and manufacturing sectors, a rebound in GDP is expected in the second quarter of 2019. Inflation for the next five years is expected to remain stable at 5,1 percent. The Monetary Policy Committee unanimously decided to reduce the repurchase rate by 25 basis points to 6.5 percent per annum.